{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_37","type":"agent_message","text":"Updated [PostgresqlTests.java](/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge5/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/forge_worktrees/3783-97c79a30/tests/src/org.postgresql/postgresql/42.7.3/src/test/java/postgresql/PostgresqlTests.java) to use the same Docker lifecycle pattern as the other PostgreSQL tests in this repo: start the container detached, bind Postgres to an ephemeral host port, resolve that port via `docker inspect`, and stop the container with `docker rm -f` in `@AfterAll`. The failure was a shared test-fixture race: the old test used fixed `localhost:5432` plus a non-blocking `process.destroy()`, so the native phase could hit the still-running database from the JVM phase and `commitAndRollback()` failed with `relation \"foo\" already exists`.\n\nVerified with the exact gate command:\n```bash\nGRAALVM_HOME=/home/vjovanov/gdrive/bin/graalvm-jdk-25.0.3+9.1 GVM_TCK_NATIVE_IMAGE_MODE=current-defaults JAVA_HOME=/home/vjovanov/gdrive/bin/graalvm-jdk-25.0.3+9.1 ./gradlew testInfra -Pcoordinates=org.postgresql:postgresql:42.7.11 -Pparallelism=1 --stacktrace\n```\nIt now finishes with `BUILD SUCCESSFUL`, and `build/command-logs/test-org.postgresql-postgresql-42.7.11.log` shows `postgresql.PostgresqlTests > commitAndRollback() SUCCESSFUL`.\n\nThere were already unrelated modified `stats/.../stats.json` files in the worktree; I left those untouched."}}
